text.div:
Generated Narrative: StructureDefinition ext-R5-SubstanceProtein

NameFlagsCard.TypeDescription & Constraints
Extension 0..*Extension(4.0.1)A SubstanceProtein is defined as a single unit of a linear amino acid sequence, or a combination of subunits that are either covalently linked or have a defined invariant stoichiometric relationship. This includes all synthetic, recombinant and purified SubstanceProteins of defined sequence, whether the use is therapeutic or prophylactic. This set of elements will be used to describe albumins, coagulation factors, cytokines, growth factors, peptide/SubstanceProtein hormones, enzymes, toxins, toxoids, recombinant vaccines, and immunomodulators
Slices for extension 0..*ExtensionExtension
Slice: Unordered, Open by value:url
extension:sequenceType 0..1ExtensionThe SubstanceProtein descriptive elements will only be used when a complete or partial amino acid sequence is available or derivable from a nucleic acid sequence
url 1..1uri"http://hl7.org/fhir/5.0/StructureDefinition/extension-SubstanceProtein.sequenceType"
value[x] 0..1CodeableConceptThe SubstanceProtein descriptive elements will only be used when a complete or partial amino acid sequence is available or derivable from a nucleic acid sequence
extension:numberOfSubunits 0..1ExtensionNumber of linear sequences of amino acids linked through peptide bonds. The number of subunits constituting the SubstanceProtein shall be described. It is possible that the number of subunits can be variable
url 1..1uri"http://hl7.org/fhir/5.0/StructureDefinition/extension-SubstanceProtein.numberOfSubunits"
value[x] 0..1integerNumber of linear sequences of amino acids linked through peptide bonds. The number of subunits constituting the SubstanceProtein shall be described. It is possible that the number of subunits can be variable
extension:disulfideLinkage 0..*ExtensionThe disulphide bond between two cysteine residues either on the same subunit or on two different subunits shall be described. The position of the disulfide bonds in the SubstanceProtein shall be listed in increasing order of subunit number and position within subunit followed by the abbreviation of the amino acids involved. The disulfide linkage positions shall actually contain the amino acid Cysteine at the respective positions
url 1..1uri"http://hl7.org/fhir/5.0/StructureDefinition/extension-SubstanceProtein.disulfideLinkage"
value[x] 0..1stringThe disulphide bond between two cysteine residues either on the same subunit or on two different subunits shall be described. The position of the disulfide bonds in the SubstanceProtein shall be listed in increasing order of subunit number and position within subunit followed by the abbreviation of the amino acids involved. The disulfide linkage positions shall actually contain the amino acid Cysteine at the respective positions
extension:subunit 0..*ExtensionThis subclause refers to the description of each subunit constituting the SubstanceProtein. A subunit is a linear sequence of amino acids linked through peptide bonds. The Subunit information shall be provided when the finished SubstanceProtein is a complex of multiple sequences; subunits are not used to delineate domains within a single sequence. Subunits are listed in order of decreasing length; sequences of the same length will be ordered by decreasing molecular weight; subunits that have identical sequences will be repeated multiple times
Slices for extension 0..*ExtensionExtension
Slice: Unordered, Open by value:url
extension:subunit 0..1ExtensionIndex of primary sequences of amino acids linked through peptide bonds in order of decreasing length. Sequences of the same length will be ordered by molecular weight. Subunits that have identical sequences will be repeated and have sequential subscripts
url 1..1uri"http://hl7.org/fhir/5.0/StructureDefinition/extension-SubstanceProtein.subunit.subunit"
value[x] 0..1integerIndex of primary sequences of amino acids linked through peptide bonds in order of decreasing length. Sequences of the same length will be ordered by molecular weight. Subunits that have identical sequences will be repeated and have sequential subscripts
extension:sequence 0..1ExtensionThe sequence information shall be provided enumerating the amino acids from N- to C-terminal end using standard single-letter amino acid codes. Uppercase shall be used for L-amino acids and lowercase for D-amino acids. Transcribed SubstanceProteins will always be described using the translated sequence; for synthetic peptide containing amino acids that are not represented with a single letter code an X should be used within the sequence. The modified amino acids will be distinguished by their position in the sequence
url 1..1uri"http://hl7.org/fhir/5.0/StructureDefinition/extension-SubstanceProtein.subunit.sequence"
value[x] 0..1stringThe sequence information shall be provided enumerating the amino acids from N- to C-terminal end using standard single-letter amino acid codes. Uppercase shall be used for L-amino acids and lowercase for D-amino acids. Transcribed SubstanceProteins will always be described using the translated sequence; for synthetic peptide containing amino acids that are not represented with a single letter code an X should be used within the sequence. The modified amino acids will be distinguished by their position in the sequence
extension:length 0..1ExtensionLength of linear sequences of amino acids contained in the subunit
url 1..1uri"http://hl7.org/fhir/5.0/StructureDefinition/extension-SubstanceProtein.subunit.length"
value[x] 0..1integerLength of linear sequences of amino acids contained in the subunit
extension:sequenceAttachment 0..1ExtensionThe sequence information shall be provided enumerating the amino acids from N- to C-terminal end using standard single-letter amino acid codes. Uppercase shall be used for L-amino acids and lowercase for D-amino acids. Transcribed SubstanceProteins will always be described using the translated sequence; for synthetic peptide containing amino acids that are not represented with a single letter code an X should be used within the sequence. The modified amino acids will be distinguished by their position in the sequence
url 1..1uri"http://hl7.org/fhir/5.0/StructureDefinition/extension-SubstanceProtein.subunit.sequenceAttachment"
value[x] 0..1AttachmentThe sequence information shall be provided enumerating the amino acids from N- to C-terminal end using standard single-letter amino acid codes. Uppercase shall be used for L-amino acids and lowercase for D-amino acids. Transcribed SubstanceProteins will always be described using the translated sequence; for synthetic peptide containing amino acids that are not represented with a single letter code an X should be used within the sequence. The modified amino acids will be distinguished by their position in the sequence
extension:nTerminalModificationId 0..1ExtensionUnique identifier for molecular fragment modification based on the ISO 11238 Substance ID
url 1..1uri"http://hl7.org/fhir/5.0/StructureDefinition/extension-SubstanceProtein.subunit.nTerminalModificationId"
value[x] 0..1IdentifierUnique identifier for molecular fragment modification based on the ISO 11238 Substance ID
extension:nTerminalModification 0..1ExtensionThe name of the fragment modified at the N-terminal of the SubstanceProtein shall be specified
url 1..1uri"http://hl7.org/fhir/5.0/StructureDefinition/extension-SubstanceProtein.subunit.nTerminalModification"
value[x] 0..1stringThe name of the fragment modified at the N-terminal of the SubstanceProtein shall be specified
extension:cTerminalModificationId 0..1ExtensionUnique identifier for molecular fragment modification based on the ISO 11238 Substance ID
url 1..1uri"http://hl7.org/fhir/5.0/StructureDefinition/extension-SubstanceProtein.subunit.cTerminalModificationId"
value[x] 0..1IdentifierUnique identifier for molecular fragment modification based on the ISO 11238 Substance ID
extension:cTerminalModification 0..1ExtensionThe modification at the C-terminal shall be specified
url 1..1uri"http://hl7.org/fhir/5.0/StructureDefinition/extension-SubstanceProtein.subunit.cTerminalModification"
value[x] 0..1stringThe modification at the C-terminal shall be specified
url 1..1uri"http://hl7.org/fhir/5.0/StructureDefinition/extension-SubstanceProtein.subunit"
value[x] 0..0Value of extension
url 1..1uri"http://hl7.org/fhir/5.0/StructureDefinition/extension-SubstanceProtein"
value[x] 0..0Value of extension

name: ExtensionSubstanceProtein
title: Cross-version Extension `R5.SubstanceProtein` for use in FHIR R4
description: This cross-version extension represents the FHIR R5 element `SubstanceProtein` for use in FHIR R4.
purpose:
This extension is part of the cross-version definitions generated to enable use of the
element `SubstanceProtein` as defined in FHIR R5
in FHIR R4.

The source element is defined as:
`SubstanceProtein` 0..* `SubstanceProtein`

Across FHIR versions, the element set has been mapped as:
* R5 `SubstanceProtein` 0..* `SubstanceProtein`

Element `SubstanceProtein` is not mapped to FHIR R4, since FHIR R5 `SubstanceProtein` is not mapped.

element.short: A SubstanceProtein is defined as a single unit of a linear amino acid sequence, or a combination of subunits that are either covalently linked or have a defined invariant stoichiometric relationship. This includes all synthetic, recombinant and purified SubstanceProteins of defined sequence, whether the use is therapeutic or prophylactic. This set of elements will be used to describe albumins, coagulation factors, cytokines, growth factors, peptide/SubstanceProtein hormones, enzymes, toxins, toxoids, recombinant vaccines, and immunomodulators
element.definition: A SubstanceProtein is defined as a single unit of a linear amino acid sequence, or a combination of subunits that are either covalently linked or have a defined invariant stoichiometric relationship. This includes all synthetic, recombinant and purified SubstanceProteins of defined sequence, whether the use is therapeutic or prophylactic. This set of elements will be used to describe albumins, coagulation factors, cytokines, growth factors, peptide/SubstanceProtein hormones, enzymes, toxins, toxoids, recombinant vaccines, and immunomodulators.

element.short: The SubstanceProtein descriptive elements will only be used when a complete or partial amino acid sequence is available or derivable from a nucleic acid sequence
element.definition: The SubstanceProtein descriptive elements will only be used when a complete or partial amino acid sequence is available or derivable from a nucleic acid sequence.
element.requirements: Element `SubstanceProtein.sequenceType` is not mapped to FHIR R4, since FHIR R5 `SubstanceProtein` is not mapped.

element.short: The SubstanceProtein descriptive elements will only be used when a complete or partial amino acid sequence is available or derivable from a nucleic acid sequence

element.short: Number of linear sequences of amino acids linked through peptide bonds. The number of subunits constituting the SubstanceProtein shall be described. It is possible that the number of subunits can be variable

element.short: The disulphide bond between two cysteine residues either on the same subunit or on two different subunits shall be described. The position of the disulfide bonds in the SubstanceProtein shall be listed in increasing order of subunit number and position within subunit followed by the abbreviation of the amino acids involved. The disulfide linkage positions shall actually contain the amino acid Cysteine at the respective positions

element.short: This subclause refers to the description of each subunit constituting the SubstanceProtein. A subunit is a linear sequence of amino acids linked through peptide bonds. The Subunit information shall be provided when the finished SubstanceProtein is a complex of multiple sequences; subunits are not used to delineate domains within a single sequence. Subunits are listed in order of decreasing length; sequences of the same length will be ordered by decreasing molecular weight; subunits that have identical sequences will be repeated multiple times

element.short: The sequence information shall be provided enumerating the amino acids from N- to C-terminal end using standard single-letter amino acid codes. Uppercase shall be used for L-amino acids and lowercase for D-amino acids. Transcribed SubstanceProteins will always be described using the translated sequence; for synthetic peptide containing amino acids that are not represented with a single letter code an X should be used within the sequence. The modified amino acids will be distinguished by their position in the sequence
